WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:55.889 --> 00:00:56.889
[music]

00:01:00.022 --> 00:01:01.922
[Peter] So here we are, Downtown Starke.

00:01:01.922 --> 00:01:05.413
-Chief Deputy, should I call you Brad?
-Call me Brad.

00:01:05.699 --> 00:01:09.660
[Peter] This town, pretty much
the economy is built off the prison, right?

00:01:09.660 --> 00:01:14.460
Yes. Prison industry is still
one of the largest economic drivers of all.

00:01:14.755 --> 00:01:17.678
Now this building right here,
this is an old bank building.

00:01:17.678 --> 00:01:19.328
We can go in here if you want to.

00:01:19.923 --> 00:01:21.648
We got a camera going, Susan.

00:01:21.648 --> 00:01:22.992
-What's in the safe?

00:01:22.992 --> 00:01:25.216
-Storage.
-That's an old classic door.

00:01:26.470 --> 00:01:28.170
Not so much money in here anymore.

00:01:28.516 --> 00:01:29.586
[Susan] No money.

00:01:29.586 --> 00:01:31.625
-Those are some secure CDs.

00:01:32.407 --> 00:01:34.928
Okay, so what was it before prisons here?

00:01:35.173 --> 00:01:38.400
Railroad came through.
It was a railroad stop.

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:41.725
Once Flagler built the East Coast Railroad…

00:01:41.725 --> 00:01:42.510
-Yep

00:01:42.510 --> 00:01:44.471
…this was a spur coming off of that.

00:01:44.471 --> 00:01:48.696
And then not long after, Camp Blanding,
which is about six miles to the east…

00:01:48.696 --> 00:01:49.316
-Okay.

00:01:49.316 --> 00:01:53.056
…that became a training grounds
for World War II.

00:01:53.609 --> 00:01:55.832
At one point, Camp Blanding,

00:01:55.832 --> 00:01:59.182
because of all the people
that were training to go over into Europe,

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:03.325
I want to say it was like
the second or third largest city

00:02:03.325 --> 00:02:06.572
in the state of Florida because of
the population that was out there.

00:02:06.572 --> 00:02:07.360
-Okay.

00:02:08.211 --> 00:02:12.320
[Brad] So we're going to be heading to a
couple of different correctional facilities

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:15.092
and the one prison in the state of Florida.

00:02:15.303 --> 00:02:18.239
I'll put up a map here,
but we're in Starke.

00:02:18.239 --> 00:02:22.040
-We're going to Raiford and Lake Butler.
-Correct.

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:26.460
Which is, like Starke, even maybe more so
tied into the prison economy.

00:02:26.460 --> 00:02:27.097
-Yeah.

00:02:27.097 --> 00:02:29.827
So you have the work crews
that come out of the prisons,

00:02:29.827 --> 00:02:32.128
clean up the side of the highways,
that sort of stuff?

00:02:32.128 --> 00:02:33.765
Clean up the side of the highways.

00:02:33.765 --> 00:02:36.402
We got a project going on
at the courthouse right now

00:02:36.402 --> 00:02:39.836
where we're doing
some secured parking for our judges.

00:02:39.836 --> 00:02:42.711
And the inmates actually came out
and built the walls.

00:02:43.086 --> 00:02:47.550
There was a day in time back
many years ago where it was forced labor.

00:02:48.020 --> 00:02:51.632
And obviously that was
ruled unconstitutional.

00:02:51.900 --> 00:02:53.931
Now it's voluntary.

00:02:54.360 --> 00:02:57.101
So if the inmate wants to work outside

00:02:57.101 --> 00:02:59.735
and they pass
the security screenings that they do,

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:02.384
they do get paid for their effort.

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:05.213
So this is old world Florida right here.

00:03:05.213 --> 00:03:07.030
-This is the real deal.
-I love this street.

00:03:07.030 --> 00:03:10.420
Now you can see some of these houses,
this one's been redone.

00:03:10.420 --> 00:03:13.326
And when they redo them, they're gorgeous.

00:03:13.393 --> 00:03:16.129
You know, I always think back 50 years ago

00:03:16.377 --> 00:03:18.192
when these houses were originally built.

00:03:18.192 --> 00:03:22.001
The craftsmanship
and the style is just so neat.

00:03:22.340 --> 00:03:24.240
So this is my father's childhood home.

00:03:24.493 --> 00:03:27.809
I used to give my parents a hard time
about not getting to grow up here

00:03:28.123 --> 00:03:29.339
in Bradford County.

00:03:29.339 --> 00:03:32.235
But my dad said that I was created
there in that house.

00:03:32.235 --> 00:03:34.400
So it's got some sentimental value to me.

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:35.679
-You grew up in Miami, right?

00:03:35.679 --> 00:03:36.679
Grew up in Miami.

00:03:40.619 --> 00:03:44.456
We're going to pull in here real quick.
This is Danielle Smith, no relation.

00:03:44.730 --> 00:03:47.540
But she's a very dynamic person
in the community.

00:03:47.540 --> 00:03:50.140
-And I wanted you to meet her real quick.
-All right.

00:03:50.590 --> 00:03:54.827
Guys, Starke has a feeling
I can't put a finger on yet.

00:03:55.270 --> 00:03:56.394
Old world stuff.

00:03:56.770 --> 00:03:58.504
Got a deep south feeling.

00:03:58.504 --> 00:04:02.014
As they say, the more south you go,
the more north it gets in Florida.

00:04:02.014 --> 00:04:04.060
So this is like northern Florida,
deep south.

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:05.160
Ooh, that smells good.

00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:06.700
[Brad] Danielle.

00:04:07.293 --> 00:04:08.648
[Peter] What's going on out here?

00:04:08.648 --> 00:04:11.151
-I got a food truck out here in Starke.
I got a car wash.

00:04:11.151 --> 00:04:13.460
-Good food?
-Oh, yeah, good food. Good barbecue.

00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:15.555
-Best in town?
-Best in town.

00:04:15.555 --> 00:04:17.205
I got my buddy Brad here with me.

00:04:18.169 --> 00:04:19.661
Is he your best customer?

00:04:19.661 --> 00:04:21.730
He's one of my best customers, I will say.

00:04:21.730 --> 00:04:23.743
The first time I met her,

00:04:23.991 --> 00:04:26.539
I was at my mom and dad's office.

00:04:26.539 --> 00:04:28.583
And I see her come running up on foot.

00:04:28.780 --> 00:04:30.648
She runs right up to my mom,

00:04:30.648 --> 00:04:33.861
gets her car keys
and brings it back to do the car wash.

00:04:34.193 --> 00:04:36.922
And then drove her car
back to the office and dropped it off

00:04:36.923 --> 00:04:38.723
and then ran back down here on foot.

00:04:39.266 --> 00:04:41.714
-And it's about a mile down the road.
-That's service.

00:04:42.010 --> 00:04:45.455
Tell us, 'cause this video is about
the prison system in the area.

00:04:45.455 --> 00:04:48.050
Do you have a lot of those workers
coming in here?

00:04:48.050 --> 00:04:51.537
So, I have prison…
you know, come in looking for a job.

00:04:51.537 --> 00:04:53.981
You know, when they transition
or just trying to find out.

00:04:53.981 --> 00:04:55.520
Oh, when they get out of prison?

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:59.048
If they were local and you know them,
you build a relationship with people.

00:04:59.048 --> 00:05:01.295
-It's all about trust.
-It's all about trust, yeah.

00:05:01.295 --> 00:05:03.570
But you have no problem
giving someone a second chance?

00:05:03.848 --> 00:05:06.028
Listen, just because,
you know, people in prison,

00:05:06.028 --> 00:05:07.872
you got good people, you got bad people.

00:05:07.872 --> 00:05:10.618
So, a lot of them
looking to change their lives.

00:05:10.618 --> 00:05:12.245
You know, looking for opportunity.

00:05:12.312 --> 00:05:14.827
Some will, some won't, so what, move on.

00:05:14.827 --> 00:05:16.290
That's the thing, you know.

00:05:16.290 --> 00:05:19.368
But everybody, honestly,
deserves a fair chance.

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:25.670
[Peter] Okay, a little detour
into the county jail.

00:05:25.670 --> 00:05:27.627
[Brad] So, this is our pod control.

00:05:27.694 --> 00:05:30.030
This is basically the local side of things.

00:05:30.030 --> 00:05:31.027
This is local.

00:05:31.027 --> 00:05:35.045
They get arrested on the initial charges
and they're housed here.

00:05:35.045 --> 00:05:36.365
That's a mixed population.

00:05:36.365 --> 00:05:39.186
So there could be a murderer all the way to

00:05:39.186 --> 00:05:43.470
somebody that didn't pay child support
housed in here at any given time.

00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:45.481
-So it's a unique situation.
-Okay.

00:05:45.770 --> 00:05:49.884
And this woman over here is sort of
looking at the cameras, managing everyone.

00:05:50.155 --> 00:05:52.350
'Cause we do have people
in cells out here, right?

00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:53.975
We have people in cells.

00:05:53.975 --> 00:05:55.391
They have access to phones.

00:05:55.391 --> 00:05:56.759
They have access to books.

00:05:56.759 --> 00:05:58.235
We feed them in there.

00:05:58.235 --> 00:06:00.661
And then we also have a section
where we can take them out

00:06:00.661 --> 00:06:04.531
for a period of time
every day in a courtyard area.

00:06:04.531 --> 00:06:06.225
[Peter] All the cells here?
Is that what's…

00:06:06.225 --> 00:06:10.030
[woman] Yes. This controls all of
the access doors to each of the areas

00:06:10.030 --> 00:06:13.849
to include all the pods as well as
the individual cells that we have.

00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:18.719
So that can be operated as well as
access to the entire pod area.

00:06:19.267 --> 00:06:22.148
I don't know if I should
have this on camera.

00:06:22.148 --> 00:06:23.831
Once this video goes live on YouTube,

00:06:23.832 --> 00:06:26.857
they might be watching this video
on YouTube talking about this.

00:06:26.857 --> 00:06:27.702
Yeah.

00:06:27.702 --> 00:06:29.296
That's sort of funny, huh?

00:06:29.296 --> 00:06:30.296
Or not?

00:06:30.296 --> 00:06:35.320
-I mean, well, they don't have
access to live Internet here.

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:39.279
Not to say they don't get on their phones
or their video calls and somebody's like,

00:06:39.279 --> 00:06:40.738
"Hey, look what we saw."

00:06:40.738 --> 00:06:42.044
Yeah, "Look what we saw."

00:06:42.051 --> 00:06:45.138
You know, but they don't
have access to it like right here.

00:06:45.138 --> 00:06:46.172
They shouldn't.

00:06:46.239 --> 00:06:48.688
I am the programs coordinator
here at the jail.

00:06:48.688 --> 00:06:53.780
So I help to oversee any of the efforts
for the individuals to better themselves

00:06:53.780 --> 00:06:57.684
or to try to make good use
of their time while they're here.

00:06:57.751 --> 00:06:58.751
Rewarding work?

00:06:59.088 --> 00:07:00.087
Very.

00:07:00.087 --> 00:07:02.429
-When it works?
-When it works it's always…

00:07:02.429 --> 00:07:04.306
-And this is your mother?
-This is my mother.

00:07:04.306 --> 00:07:08.350
And you were saying off camera,
third generation, in corrections.

00:07:08.350 --> 00:07:10.248
-She's the third.
-She's the third.

00:07:10.570 --> 00:07:12.990
-You came down from Tennessee.
-Yes.

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:16.630
When the going gets tough in the economy,
this is a great line of work.

00:07:16.630 --> 00:07:17.630
Absolutely.

00:07:17.630 --> 00:07:19.883
-That's why you guys came from Tennessee?
-Absolutely.

00:07:19.883 --> 00:07:23.649
My father was self-employed
and owned several businesses in Tennessee.

00:07:23.967 --> 00:07:27.640
And as the economy
kind of tanked and went downhill,

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:29.389
he was looking for retirement.

00:07:29.389 --> 00:07:31.170
-Oh, okay.
-And with the benefits.

00:07:31.170 --> 00:07:33.109
And that's how we ended up down here.

00:07:33.109 --> 00:07:36.392
Then when I came along and was old enough
and started having my family

00:07:36.393 --> 00:07:40.562
in order to provide
good insurance and the benefits

00:07:40.562 --> 00:07:43.076
that you're always looking for
with small kids and everything,

00:07:43.076 --> 00:07:45.873
then I went to
the Department of Corrections as well.

00:07:45.873 --> 00:07:48.670
It was one of the best jobs
you could get in the area.

00:07:49.012 --> 00:07:52.024
-You were in at the state prison?
-Mm-hmm. Yes.

00:07:52.024 --> 00:07:53.465
We're going there next.

00:07:53.466 --> 00:07:55.045
My grandfather started there.

00:07:55.045 --> 00:07:56.948
He was hired on at Florida State Prison.

00:07:56.948 --> 00:07:58.268
He was one of the…

00:07:58.268 --> 00:08:03.535
He was around for various high-profile
inmates who were executed out there.

00:08:04.075 --> 00:08:05.360
Ted Bundy.

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:07.315
-Ted Bundy?
-The early '80s.

00:08:08.039 --> 00:08:11.130
And then he retired
in the late '90s from out there.

00:08:11.130 --> 00:08:14.243
And then, of course, she worked there
and then I actually worked there.

00:08:14.243 --> 00:08:16.550
-So it's going…
-So it's like… Yeah.

00:08:17.123 --> 00:08:18.563
-Do you have kids?
-I do.

00:08:18.570 --> 00:08:20.399
-They're probably a bit young, but…
-They are.

00:08:20.399 --> 00:08:23.090
…do you want them to work there
when they grow up? Would you?

00:08:23.090 --> 00:08:25.627
Do you want to keep this lineage going?

00:08:26.101 --> 00:08:29.511
I know that within corrections

00:08:29.511 --> 00:08:31.853
and within any type of law enforcement

00:08:31.854 --> 00:08:34.204
or anything like that,
that's where my heart is.

00:08:34.743 --> 00:08:36.849
So I know it can be rewarding.

00:08:36.849 --> 00:08:39.503
I know it can be… fun.

00:08:39.503 --> 00:08:41.017
I know it can be all the things.

00:08:41.017 --> 00:08:43.475
It can be stressful of course,
just nature of the work.

00:08:43.475 --> 00:08:46.660
But I know that if that's
where their heart lies

00:08:46.661 --> 00:08:49.466
and that's something they're interested in,
I would support them.

00:08:49.466 --> 00:08:51.806
-So it's where your heart is.
-Yep.

00:08:51.806 --> 00:08:53.140
What do you get out of it?

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:56.790
There's a certain fulfillment
in knowing that you've

00:08:57.262 --> 00:08:58.651
helped an underdog,

00:08:58.652 --> 00:09:01.253
someone who has struggled

00:09:01.253 --> 00:09:04.362
or who has had bad luck all along the way,

00:09:04.362 --> 00:09:07.218
and everything that could possibly
go wrong and against them has,

00:09:07.745 --> 00:09:11.092
and then to be able to come in and
give them a little bit of encouragement

00:09:11.098 --> 00:09:14.248
or give them some tools or whatever it is
that they need to start helping them…

00:09:14.248 --> 00:09:17.263
-…to get out of a cycle of being in this.
-Okay.

00:09:17.776 --> 00:09:19.450
then it's like, hah.

00:09:19.450 --> 00:09:21.950
Especially if that goes to their kids.

00:09:21.950 --> 00:09:25.630
-So you get connected
to them a little emotionally.

00:09:25.630 --> 00:09:26.676
Yeah, it can.

00:09:26.676 --> 00:09:29.286
I mean, it is definitely a line
that you have to balance.

00:09:29.286 --> 00:09:31.332
-I'd imagine, yeah.
-You know, you can't…

00:09:31.830 --> 00:09:33.977
But I think over the years,

00:09:33.978 --> 00:09:36.490
I've been able to do that
and keep that professionalism,

00:09:36.490 --> 00:09:40.189
but also that I care
and I do want to see you do better

00:09:40.189 --> 00:09:41.681
and I do want to see you do well.

00:09:41.748 --> 00:09:44.975
That's one of the differences that
you'll see with the state prison system

00:09:44.975 --> 00:09:47.147
and with the jails

00:09:47.556 --> 00:09:50.370
is most of the people we deal with in here

00:09:50.693 --> 00:09:52.543
are people that are in our community.

00:09:52.796 --> 00:09:55.322
We've either watched them grow up.

00:09:55.322 --> 00:09:58.168
They've gone to school with us,
our children.

00:09:58.448 --> 00:09:59.834
We know these people.

00:10:00.090 --> 00:10:02.840
So if we can do anything
to positively impact

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:05.552
and kind of help them out,
then that's great.

00:10:05.552 --> 00:10:08.713
So there's times when
we can be out locally

00:10:08.945 --> 00:10:11.374
and we have people that approach us

00:10:11.374 --> 00:10:14.363
and they talk to us
just like anybody else.

00:10:17.780 --> 00:10:19.106
[Peter] Florida State Prison.

00:10:19.106 --> 00:10:21.788
[Brad] Oh, yeah. This is the start
of the property right here.

00:10:21.788 --> 00:10:23.786
The highest security you can get.

00:10:23.786 --> 00:10:27.297
And it's death row, which it's
the end of the line for many of them.

00:10:30.465 --> 00:10:33.435
Basically, as far as you can see
to the county line,

00:10:33.435 --> 00:10:35.461
which is about a mile up the road there

00:10:35.981 --> 00:10:37.820
is Florida State Prison.

00:10:37.820 --> 00:10:40.107
To the left are some officer housing

00:10:40.107 --> 00:10:42.842
and then there are some
administrative buildings and a warehouse.

00:10:42.909 --> 00:10:45.646
Out here in these fields they raise cattle.

00:10:45.646 --> 00:10:48.475
They raise crops to help feed the inmates.

00:10:49.182 --> 00:10:53.107
We've actually set the record
this past year in 2025

00:10:53.107 --> 00:10:56.551
for the number of people
that have been put to death for the year.

00:10:56.551 --> 00:10:58.930
-And they use an injection now.
It's not the chair, right?

00:10:58.930 --> 00:10:59.930
Correct.

00:11:00.350 --> 00:11:03.156
Because before it was,
I read it was the chair.

00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:06.709
And they would take people
from the community.

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:08.230
Nobody knew who it was.

00:11:08.230 --> 00:11:12.017
Different people, maybe even every time,
they got paid like $150 to do it.

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:13.630
Yeah, the executioner.

00:11:13.630 --> 00:11:15.090
The executioner, right.

00:11:15.091 --> 00:11:17.120
Now, they still do that with the injection.

00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:19.510
There's a way that they actually set it up.

00:11:19.510 --> 00:11:22.159
And they don't identify
who the executioner is.

00:11:24.396 --> 00:11:26.931
[Brad] I actually witnessed
one of the executions

00:11:26.932 --> 00:11:28.816
and it was by lethal injection.

00:11:28.816 --> 00:11:30.266
It was kind of a last minute.

00:11:30.656 --> 00:11:33.748
The courts turned down his appeal

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:36.023
and the execution moved forward.

00:11:36.023 --> 00:11:38.043
They needed to bring in
witnesses to see it.

00:11:38.043 --> 00:11:39.644
They called the office.

00:11:39.644 --> 00:11:41.610
I happened to be the one
that answered the phone.

00:11:41.610 --> 00:11:44.623
And they asked if we had any officers
that would come

00:11:45.303 --> 00:11:48.063
be on the witness panel.

00:11:48.590 --> 00:11:50.966
-How heavy was that day?
What was that like?

00:11:50.966 --> 00:11:54.650
It was a very interesting experience.

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:57.630
Correctional officers,
they have certain people identified

00:11:57.630 --> 00:12:01.479
to work in certain spots of the process.

00:12:01.479 --> 00:12:05.547
The most mature, respectful,
professional individuals

00:12:05.547 --> 00:12:09.147
are the ones that are actually
working right up close to

00:12:09.147 --> 00:12:11.130
where the execution is occurring.

00:12:11.698 --> 00:12:13.174
So they have a whole process.

00:12:13.174 --> 00:12:15.680
They meet off site for the witnesses.

00:12:15.680 --> 00:12:19.358
It could be family members
of the person being put to death

00:12:19.358 --> 00:12:23.706
or it could be family members
of the person that was victimized.

00:12:23.706 --> 00:12:26.490
Then they also have independent
witnesses that come in.

00:12:26.805 --> 00:12:31.724
It was regimented, very medical
type of process that took place.

00:12:31.930 --> 00:12:34.829
They explained to us the process
going into it so we knew.

00:12:34.829 --> 00:12:38.734
But there wasn't a word spoken
as far as the witness panel

00:12:39.121 --> 00:12:42.564
probably for about an hour
it was just complete silence

00:12:42.862 --> 00:12:45.685
from the moment
that we left the meeting spot

00:12:45.919 --> 00:12:49.384
to going in, witnessing it,
and then leaving out of there.

00:12:49.823 --> 00:12:50.823
-Wow.

00:12:50.823 --> 00:12:53.036
-It was a very somber,

00:12:53.037 --> 00:12:55.043
serious point in time.

00:12:55.616 --> 00:12:59.795
Now, this little building that comes out
towards us right here at the end,

00:13:00.059 --> 00:13:01.734
see how you got the wings going

00:13:02.636 --> 00:13:04.985
those ways and then you got
the one coming out this end?

00:13:04.985 --> 00:13:05.585
-Yep.

00:13:05.585 --> 00:13:07.835
-That's the death chamber
on the bottom floor.

00:13:09.010 --> 00:13:12.469
The rest of the wings
are where the inmates are housed.

00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:14.760
And then you'll see these areas.

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:17.377
They look like containment areas

00:13:17.378 --> 00:13:20.109
right here, fenced in areas.

00:13:20.109 --> 00:13:22.543
And that's where they'll
bring them out if they're isolated

00:13:22.543 --> 00:13:24.948
and aren't allowed
to have contact with anybody else,

00:13:24.948 --> 00:13:27.844
they have their own little section
that they're allowed to come out.

00:13:27.844 --> 00:13:29.470
You can hear them right now.

00:13:29.996 --> 00:13:31.020
Oh, yeah.

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:33.335
Can you stop for a sec? Is it alright?

00:13:33.335 --> 00:13:36.432
Can we show the video
of where you said death row was?

00:13:36.432 --> 00:13:37.432
Yeah. Yeah.

00:13:37.432 --> 00:13:39.550
I mean, I don't want to get you in trouble.

00:13:39.550 --> 00:13:41.787
It's not gonna get me in trouble.
We're driving through.

00:13:44.164 --> 00:13:46.188
[inmates speaking in the distance]

00:13:52.060 --> 00:13:53.660
[Peter] Is it like that all day?

00:13:53.996 --> 00:13:55.520
[Brad] Not all day.

00:13:55.520 --> 00:13:57.270
You know, those are the ones that are…

00:13:57.270 --> 00:13:59.538
I don't know, maybe…
I think they're inside, right?

00:13:59.538 --> 00:14:00.660
Are they inside?

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:02.961
-I don't see anyone outside.
-I don't see anybody outside.

00:14:02.961 --> 00:14:04.880
So, yeah, it could be like that.

