00:15:34.225 --> 00:15:35.513
Now back to the story.

00:15:36.980 --> 00:15:40.366
[Brad] My father was a prison guard,
but he worked the tower.

00:15:40.366 --> 00:15:44.429
He said it was a draining job
that you sat day in and day out

00:15:44.429 --> 00:15:47.300
just watching these secured fence areas

00:15:47.301 --> 00:15:50.426
to make sure nobody's trying to escape.

00:15:50.780 --> 00:15:55.760
-And it's 99.999% of your time
is watching nothing happening.

00:15:55.761 --> 00:15:56.963
Watching nothing happen.

00:15:56.976 --> 00:16:01.101
But that one moment that something does
happen, you have to stop the person.

00:16:01.101 --> 00:16:02.872
-You can't miss it.
-Yeah, you can't miss it.

00:16:02.872 --> 00:16:05.456
Before all  the good cameras
and motion sensors.

00:16:06.065 --> 00:16:08.734
[Peter] It's such an
interesting feel out here.

00:16:08.734 --> 00:16:11.003
You have this cutesy little town,

00:16:11.003 --> 00:16:14.555
and then you have some of the most
hardened criminals right here.

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:16.864
The only place for death row in the state.

00:16:18.278 --> 00:16:20.313
So there's just… it's heavy.

00:16:20.313 --> 00:16:23.263
The death penalty
is obviously a very sticky topic.

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:27.686
Now, when it hits home,
as in it affects me,

00:16:27.687 --> 00:16:29.711
as in someone murders my mother,

00:16:30.370 --> 00:16:32.370
do I want them to get the death penalty?

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:36.608
I don't know right now.
I'd have to feel it happen, right?

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:39.418
Personally, maybe it would be very clear.

00:16:39.418 --> 00:16:40.418
Maybe it'd be like

00:16:41.195 --> 00:16:43.444
that person deserves to be off this earth,

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:48.993
or maybe I'd have some
bit of empathy for that not to happen.

00:16:48.993 --> 00:16:51.070
I don't know. I haven't been there, right?

00:16:51.070 --> 00:16:54.242
So until you've been there
it's hard to know, right?

00:16:54.242 --> 00:16:56.383
Like, if you are on
the victim side of that.

00:16:56.383 --> 00:17:00.029
Well, I mean, you know, different people
have different opinions about it.

00:17:00.029 --> 00:17:02.475
My personal opinion is I fully support it.

00:17:03.705 --> 00:17:06.218
I know the process that it goes through,

00:17:06.219 --> 00:17:08.413
and it takes decades

00:17:08.907 --> 00:17:11.105
from the time that
they're convicted of the crime

00:17:11.646 --> 00:17:13.304
in order to be put to death.

00:17:13.304 --> 00:17:17.169
All the appeals processes
that are in place, it is a deterrent.

00:17:17.169 --> 00:17:20.643
People know that there's that possibility
that they could be put to death.

00:17:20.906 --> 00:17:24.366
Now, this is New River that we're crossing,
going into Union County.

00:17:24.366 --> 00:17:25.751
-And the prison continues?

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:29.050
Directly across the street,
or across the county line,

00:17:29.050 --> 00:17:30.819
is Union Correctional.

00:17:30.819 --> 00:17:32.024
Okay, so separate.

00:17:32.024 --> 00:17:33.890
It's separate, different counties.

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:37.480
Now, they do have people
that are on death row living over here,

00:17:37.480 --> 00:17:41.565
and they'll transfer them over if
the warrant is signed for their execution.

00:17:42.200 --> 00:17:46.561
This is housing for correctional officers
to be readily available.

00:17:46.561 --> 00:17:50.526
If they have a major incident go down
they can recall people that are off duty

00:17:50.534 --> 00:17:52.400
to get them here to assist.

00:17:52.700 --> 00:17:55.428
-How often is it that
somebody actually escapes

00:17:55.429 --> 00:17:57.226
or that doesn't happen anymore?

00:17:57.226 --> 00:17:59.984
It is so rare for it to happen.

00:18:00.295 --> 00:18:04.859
The last time I can remember
one happening was about 10 years ago.

00:18:04.859 --> 00:18:08.265
It was an inmate that had
reached like a trustee type status

00:18:08.265 --> 00:18:12.632
and was working outside
the prison walls basically.

00:18:12.959 --> 00:18:15.970
As soon as they realized
he had walked off or ran off,

00:18:16.210 --> 00:18:18.272
there was a two-day
search for this guy.

00:18:18.573 --> 00:18:20.122
The thickest woods, they have

00:18:20.563 --> 00:18:24.166
several bloodhound units

00:18:24.166 --> 00:18:28.118
where we had a dog on the ground
for two days straight.

00:18:28.562 --> 00:18:31.616
And as soon as that dog would tire out,
they'd put another one on the ground

00:18:31.616 --> 00:18:33.903
and chase that guy the whole time.

00:18:33.903 --> 00:18:36.800
He had no time
to stop and relax or anything.

00:18:36.801 --> 00:18:41.630
By the end of the two days, he was so
tired, so hungry and eaten up by bugs

00:18:41.630 --> 00:18:45.700
and torn up by the thick brush
that he was having to go through

00:18:46.224 --> 00:18:49.453
that he came out onto the street
and surrendered to an officer

00:18:49.453 --> 00:18:51.103
that was set up on the perimeter.

00:18:51.347 --> 00:18:53.815
We're going down here
is where the graveyard is.

00:18:53.815 --> 00:18:54.815
-Graveyard?

00:18:54.815 --> 00:19:00.320
They actually have a cemetery
for inmates that have died while in custody

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:03.300
and we're pulling up to it here
in just a minute.

00:19:06.422 --> 00:19:07.422
Here's a placard.

00:19:08.260 --> 00:19:11.360
"This grounds renovation,
beautification and perpetual…

00:19:12.013 --> 00:19:13.623
is the result of hard work…

00:19:14.137 --> 00:19:15.647
private donation…"

00:19:15.647 --> 00:19:19.751
[Peter] Okay so these are all convicts
that died in the prison?

00:19:19.751 --> 00:19:20.444
-Yes.

00:19:20.444 --> 00:19:22.750
-No family members?
Nobody's claimed the body

00:19:23.179 --> 00:19:26.003
and they have the right to a burial.

00:19:26.003 --> 00:19:28.660
And like like this says
at the very bottom it says

00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:32.827
"They pay their debt to society,
may God remit their debt to him."

00:19:34.460 --> 00:19:36.291
1997 on that one.

00:19:36.745 --> 00:19:37.910
-Arthur Schaefer.

00:19:40.490 --> 00:19:42.207
-James Warren.
-'99.

00:19:47.585 --> 00:19:49.331
Milson Joseph Edward.

00:19:50.790 --> 00:19:52.845
You're used to this stuff
it's nothing for you Brad

00:19:52.845 --> 00:19:55.363
but it's a bit wild to come into
I'm not going to lie.

00:19:55.363 --> 00:19:58.261
I'll have to say this,
I've driven out here a couple times

00:19:58.261 --> 00:19:59.909
'cause we have a training facility,

00:19:59.909 --> 00:20:02.683
firearms training out here
from time to time

00:20:02.683 --> 00:20:04.713
and I noticed the cemetery.

00:20:04.720 --> 00:20:05.920
I've never stopped here.

00:20:06.267 --> 00:20:07.950
This is my first time actually stopping

00:20:07.950 --> 00:20:10.666
and my personal thought

00:20:10.954 --> 00:20:14.657
when I first saw it and realized
what it was is you know good gracious,

00:20:14.657 --> 00:20:18.385
these are human beings
like the placard said

00:20:18.390 --> 00:20:20.908
they they paid their debt to society

00:20:21.127 --> 00:20:22.665
died while they were in prison

00:20:23.119 --> 00:20:26.080
and there was nobody there
to claim the body

00:20:26.312 --> 00:20:28.368
and this is where they lay.

00:20:28.856 --> 00:20:31.091
I commend the Department of Corrections for

00:20:32.591 --> 00:20:35.572
giving them some sort of respectful burial.

00:20:35.572 --> 00:20:37.537
-'Cause nobody would know or care.

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:39.020
Right.

00:20:39.623 --> 00:20:42.549
That's one of the things I've learned

00:20:43.063 --> 00:20:45.100
about being in this community is that

00:20:46.100 --> 00:20:47.840
the people in
the Department of Corrections,

00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:50.491
they care about the people as individuals.

00:20:51.050 --> 00:20:55.385
Even up into the point of putting somebody
to death in the death chamber.

00:20:56.508 --> 00:21:00.116
They they are giving them
respect and dignity

00:21:00.694 --> 00:21:02.095
that they probably did not…

00:21:03.035 --> 00:21:04.217
I say probably…

00:21:04.218 --> 00:21:06.830
Almost assuredly didn't give their victims

00:21:07.577 --> 00:21:09.183
any type of respect.

00:21:09.810 --> 00:21:13.034
-Wouldn't you say though, Brad,
like any profession,

00:21:13.034 --> 00:21:15.801
there are good ones
and bad ones and of course, like,

00:21:16.474 --> 00:21:19.179
there'll be a bad guy a guy in there
that's not that great.

00:21:19.179 --> 00:21:23.999
You hope to weed those guys out
and you want, like in your office,

00:21:24.421 --> 00:21:27.269
or with any profession
you want awesome doctors.

00:21:27.270 --> 00:21:28.778
You don't want malpractice.

00:21:28.778 --> 00:21:30.398
And so it's human

00:21:30.924 --> 00:21:33.178
right, to get people that are bad

00:21:33.899 --> 00:21:36.106
and that infiltrates everything

00:21:37.001 --> 00:21:38.963
and there's gonna be some of it in there.

00:21:38.963 --> 00:21:42.240
Some in here, there’s definitely
some bad YouTubers, that's for sure.

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:45.786
And you can imagine your job is to go in

00:21:45.786 --> 00:21:48.837
and deal with these populations

00:21:48.837 --> 00:21:50.333
and these particular prisons,

00:21:50.334 --> 00:21:52.384
these are some of the worst of the worst.

00:21:52.735 --> 00:21:54.850
-First degree murder, rapists.

00:21:54.850 --> 00:21:57.413
-Yeah, and it could be lower-level crimes,

00:21:57.778 --> 00:22:00.367
but they've committed
other crimes while in prison,

00:22:01.227 --> 00:22:04.007
gotten to a point where
they have to go into a higher security

00:22:04.007 --> 00:22:06.693
because they can't manage them
in lower security.

00:22:06.760 --> 00:22:10.750
Not been able to acclimate
to the prison environment.

00:22:15.205 --> 00:22:18.228
[Brad] From here to Downtown Starke
is about seven miles.

00:22:18.228 --> 00:22:21.484
That's two maximum security prisons,
seven miles.

00:22:21.780 --> 00:22:25.180
[Peter] Yeah, I wanted to drop
some info I found last night.

00:22:25.510 --> 00:22:29.199
Florida Department of Corrections
is the third biggest in the country.

00:22:29.199 --> 00:22:31.839
Which makes sense.
It's the third biggest population.

00:22:31.839 --> 00:22:35.275
Inmate population
is roughly 89,000 right now.

00:22:36.990 --> 00:22:40.961
It's the largest agency
administrated by the State of Florida

00:22:40.961 --> 00:22:43.002
with a budget of $3.3 billion.

00:22:43.908 --> 00:22:44.908
With a B.

00:22:44.908 --> 00:22:47.358
These are government jobs.
There's no third party…

00:22:48.780 --> 00:22:50.812
-It's not privatized.
-It's not privatized.

00:22:50.812 --> 00:22:54.860
They looked at, a few years ago,
doing some privatization.

00:22:54.860 --> 00:22:57.019
I think when Jeb Bush was governor.

00:22:57.426 --> 00:23:00.864
It didn't work out well, so they stopped.

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:04.473
-And we're going to meet a guy today,
former corrections officer.

00:23:04.473 --> 00:23:07.098
He agreed to be on camera
because you can't get someone

00:23:07.098 --> 00:23:08.948
currently working in there on camera.

00:23:09.356 --> 00:23:12.144
-Yeah, it's interesting.
-It's not going to happen.

00:23:12.144 --> 00:23:14.428
They are tight-knit community,

00:23:14.429 --> 00:23:18.786
and they are worried about media

00:23:18.786 --> 00:23:21.182
and talking to the public
about what's going on

00:23:21.182 --> 00:23:24.795
because they're afraid that it's
gonna be misconstrued what they say.

00:23:24.795 --> 00:23:28.276
As a creator,
I can make the best things sound terrible

00:23:28.277 --> 00:23:30.865
and the worst things
sound great with voice over,

00:23:30.865 --> 00:23:32.615
the right music, the right editing.

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:34.280
Absolutely.

00:23:34.280 --> 00:23:36.686
You never know who's coming up
with the camera and I get that

00:23:36.686 --> 00:23:39.912
because someone might have
good intentions but they might not.

00:23:40.290 --> 00:23:44.493
We were passing some signs back there
that said starting $22 an hour.

00:23:44.493 --> 00:23:46.278
-Probably a correctional officer.

00:23:46.278 --> 00:23:48.755
Right around the $50,000 a year mark.

00:23:48.755 --> 00:23:51.745
-And so the reason they have
all the prisons up here

00:23:51.745 --> 00:23:53.806
and correctional facilities,

00:23:54.365 --> 00:23:56.762
cheap land, rural communities.

00:23:56.762 --> 00:24:00.870
They had, back then, people were
worried about living around a prison,

00:24:00.870 --> 00:24:04.235
so they tried to put 'em
out in isolated areas.

00:24:04.505 --> 00:24:07.175
-Okay.
-Where there wasn't much of a population.

00:24:07.381 --> 00:24:10.213
I talked to a gentleman
about two or three years ago.

00:24:10.213 --> 00:24:13.627
He called and was looking at
purchasing a property.

00:24:13.876 --> 00:24:16.150
They were moving up from Sarasota area.

00:24:16.420 --> 00:24:21.190
The property that they really liked
and wanted to buy backed up to and adjoin

00:24:21.190 --> 00:24:23.314
the Florida State Prison property line.

00:24:23.314 --> 00:24:27.587
And his question to me was,
how safe or unsafe

00:24:27.847 --> 00:24:30.417
would it be for him
to move his family up here?

00:24:30.840 --> 00:24:33.647
And I told him
the closer you are to a prison,

00:24:34.011 --> 00:24:38.432
the less chance of an escaped prisoner
stopping to hide out at your house.

00:24:38.690 --> 00:24:43.538
They are wanting to get
as far away as fast as they can.

00:24:43.980 --> 00:24:46.963
So if your property
is right next to the prison,

00:24:47.197 --> 00:24:50.524
if they ran across your property,
they would be gone within seconds.

00:24:50.855 --> 00:24:53.188
He ended up buying it,
moving in, and loves it.

00:24:55.010 --> 00:24:56.461
[Peter] Okay, Downtown Lake Butler.

00:24:56.461 --> 00:24:58.198
-This is it.
-This is the center point.

00:24:58.198 --> 00:25:01.274
This used to be the only red light.

00:25:01.670 --> 00:25:04.070
Now they got another one around the corner.

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:06.672
This is the courthouse
and the sheriff's office

00:25:07.001 --> 00:25:09.051
and the jail is on the back side of that.

00:25:09.340 --> 00:25:10.340
-That's nice.

00:25:10.753 --> 00:25:15.717
-And I believe it's the only county
in the state that does not have a hotel.

00:25:16.210 --> 00:25:18.227
There's McDonald's right here on the right

00:25:18.227 --> 00:25:20.323
that just opened up about two years ago.

00:25:20.323 --> 00:25:22.006
So that's a big deal in a town like this.

00:25:22.006 --> 00:25:23.185
-Huge deal.
-Huge deal?

00:25:23.480 --> 00:25:24.832
[Brad] Huuge.

00:25:24.845 --> 00:25:26.485
[Peter] Everyone's pumped up on that?

00:25:26.485 --> 00:25:28.390
So I'm going to eat at the Skip's Deli's.

00:25:28.390 --> 00:25:30.193
There's the IGA right there.

00:25:30.193 --> 00:25:31.860
-Okay. Talk to the owner here.

00:25:31.860 --> 00:25:33.150
I'll meet you at Skip's.

00:25:33.150 --> 00:25:35.742
Right behind there
is Jackson's Building Supply.

00:25:35.742 --> 00:25:38.450
So a lot of locals go there
to get their hardware.

00:25:39.455 --> 00:25:41.860
[Peter] You're an early eater, Brad, huh?
11:00.

00:25:41.860 --> 00:25:42.696
-Yeah.

00:25:42.696 --> 00:25:44.337
-I'll be back in a little bit.
-All right.

00:25:44.337 --> 00:25:46.070
-I'm going to go try these guys.
-Good luck.

00:25:46.070 --> 00:25:49.220
-I got my phone on me if you need anything.
-Okay. Thanks, Brad.

00:25:53.660 --> 00:25:55.950
[man] I don't want to stand
in front of my dead plants.

00:25:55.950 --> 00:25:57.680
The freeze has killed them.

00:25:57.680 --> 00:25:59.488
-It froze, huh?
-Yeah.

00:25:59.870 --> 00:26:02.419
So you're Mike Spires. This is your market.

00:26:02.419 --> 00:26:03.985
Yeah. Four generations.

00:26:03.985 --> 00:26:05.607
-Four generations?
-Yep.

00:26:05.820 --> 00:26:09.157
I thought you'd be cool to talk to
because you deal with everyone.

00:26:09.157 --> 00:26:11.953
A store like this in a town like this,
you talk to everyone.

00:26:11.953 --> 00:26:12.603
Yeah.

00:26:12.603 --> 00:26:16.105
What's going on, would you say,
wide question, answer it any way you want.

00:26:16.112 --> 00:26:18.224
What's going on
with the prison system these days

00:26:18.224 --> 00:26:20.724
and the employment
and what you see from your shop?

00:26:21.030 --> 00:26:24.918
I know they were having
some issues with recruitment.

00:26:25.240 --> 00:26:27.048
-Oh.
-So I'm not sure.

00:26:27.048 --> 00:26:29.949
-I guess all of that's working itself out.
-Okay.

00:26:29.949 --> 00:26:32.106
I think the governor's
done a good job of

00:26:32.639 --> 00:26:34.800
trying to help the prison system out.

00:26:34.800 --> 00:26:35.370
Okay.

00:26:35.370 --> 00:26:37.363
They play a huge part in this community.

00:26:37.430 --> 00:26:38.583
It's just part of us.

00:26:38.583 --> 00:26:41.740
It's part of who we are and part of
what our community is all about.

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:43.272
-So for you, it's just totally normal.

00:26:43.272 --> 00:26:46.385
It's just another industry,
keeps the lights on, keeps things going.

00:26:46.385 --> 00:26:47.835
Yes. A big part of it.

00:26:48.210 --> 00:26:50.187
-And you got the IGA. That's a classic.

00:26:50.187 --> 00:26:52.367
-Yeah, it is.
-Been around forever.

00:26:52.367 --> 00:26:57.487
I've had… There's probably
quite a few current correctional officers

00:26:57.487 --> 00:27:00.125
that started out
in high school working here.

00:27:00.125 --> 00:27:02.664
So we were talking about that
with someone the other day

00:27:02.665 --> 00:27:04.710
and they said, yeah, IGAs.

00:27:04.710 --> 00:27:06.290
I've heard of IGAs.

00:27:06.290 --> 00:27:07.970
I said yeah, you would be surprised

00:27:07.970 --> 00:27:10.937
how many people I've talked to
just out of the blue saying,

00:27:10.937 --> 00:27:15.018
"Oh, I have a family member,
that was their first job growing up."

00:27:15.370 --> 00:27:18.886
You must hear all sorts of things
from people working in on the inside.

00:27:19.760 --> 00:27:21.645
-Family members.
-I hear.

00:27:21.645 --> 00:27:23.057
And it's tough.

00:27:23.057 --> 00:27:27.668
From what I can gather,
I can just imagine, it's a tough job.

00:27:27.880 --> 00:27:32.513
I mean, you're dealing with
a society that's not the best.

00:27:32.809 --> 00:27:35.550
-And these guys are from who knows where.
-Yeah.

00:27:35.550 --> 00:27:37.050
They're not from here, mostly.

00:27:37.370 --> 00:27:39.678
-Mostly South Florida I'll bet.
-Oh, yeah. Yeah.

00:27:39.678 --> 00:27:42.877
Most of the crime
that takes place is elsewhere.

00:27:42.877 --> 00:27:47.498
But in Raiford, which is where
the hardened criminals are,

00:27:47.849 --> 00:27:50.149
death penalty, death row,
all that's out there.

00:27:50.640 --> 00:27:53.064
If you have a chance to go ride by that.

00:27:53.064 --> 00:27:54.064
-Oh, we just did.

00:27:54.064 --> 00:27:55.690
It's a unique place out there.

00:27:55.690 --> 00:27:58.803
-And you know,
what I think goes unnoticed,

00:27:58.803 --> 00:28:02.069
the prison system, while you can
take a bunch of different angles on it,

00:28:03.280 --> 00:28:05.577
the reality we're in, if those don't exist,

00:28:05.577 --> 00:28:07.577
if our most hardened criminals
aren't there,

00:28:08.054 --> 00:28:09.404
and the people working here

00:28:10.105 --> 00:28:13.393
don't keep that going,
then all of our lives are much worse.

00:28:13.393 --> 00:28:14.950
It would be chaotic.

00:28:15.326 --> 00:28:16.925
-It'd be chaotic.
-Yep.

00:28:16.925 --> 00:28:19.499
So actually, I never even thought of

00:28:20.579 --> 00:28:22.813
thanking the corrections officer
ever in my life.

00:28:22.813 --> 00:28:25.202
And I'm sure there's some bad ones
I wouldn't want to thank,

00:28:25.202 --> 00:28:27.406
but I'm sure the majority aren't.

00:28:27.704 --> 00:28:29.280
-They do a good job.
-Oh, yeah. Yeah.

00:28:29.280 --> 00:28:31.614
And without them, we have

00:28:32.285 --> 00:28:33.654
way sketchier streets.

00:28:35.090 --> 00:28:36.555
Yes. So we're all connected.

00:28:36.555 --> 00:28:37.805
-Appreciate it.
-Yes, sir.

00:28:42.800 --> 00:28:45.421
-A lot of your customers from the…
-From the prison.

00:28:45.421 --> 00:28:48.057
And we have clear containers just for them,

00:28:48.399 --> 00:28:51.830
'cause they can't take their food in
if it's not wrapped in a clear container

00:28:51.837 --> 00:28:53.842
or some kind of saran wrap
or something like that.

00:28:53.842 --> 00:28:55.289
Oh, right.

00:28:55.700 --> 00:28:57.590
-Did you know that, Brad?
-I did not know that.

00:28:57.590 --> 00:29:00.810
-So no shank can be hidden type stuff.
-Right.

00:29:00.810 --> 00:29:02.610
-Or drugs or whatever, right?
-Right.

00:29:03.010 --> 00:29:05.420
So it's super important
for you then, these workers?

00:29:05.420 --> 00:29:06.580
Mm-hmm. Yes, sir.

00:29:06.580 --> 00:29:09.461
That's what most of
the income is around here

00:29:09.462 --> 00:29:13.803
is the prisons in Union County
unless you work at a gas station…

00:29:13.803 --> 00:29:15.801
-…or, you know…
-Sandwich shop.

00:29:15.801 --> 00:29:18.060
At the sandwich shop down here with us.

00:29:18.060 --> 00:29:20.084
Can I show the sandwiches?
Is that all right?

00:29:20.693 --> 00:29:22.243
There you go.
You go heavy on the meat.

00:29:22.243 --> 00:29:23.600
I like that.

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:24.600
Looks good.

00:29:26.800 --> 00:29:28.586
[Peter] So just nice, quaint little town.

00:29:29.133 --> 00:29:30.768
You have a job at the prison.

00:29:30.768 --> 00:29:33.394
You're making 50 grand
maybe starting, 48 grand.

00:29:33.870 --> 00:29:35.240
Work up a little bit.

00:29:35.240 --> 00:29:37.470
Maybe your wife's in there
involved somehow.

00:29:37.470 --> 00:29:39.110
You can make over 100 grand.

00:29:39.110 --> 00:29:42.600
Houses here, I'm just
guessing, $200,000, $300,000?

00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:45.153
Yeah, no, it's not any more than that.

00:29:45.220 --> 00:29:48.145
Nicer houses are about $250,000, $300,000.

00:29:48.477 --> 00:29:50.525
-So for Florida, cheap real estate?

00:29:50.525 --> 00:29:52.215
-Comparatively speaking, yes.

00:29:52.720 --> 00:29:55.220
All three counties
that we've been talking about,

00:29:55.220 --> 00:29:57.159
each county only has one high school,

00:29:57.721 --> 00:30:00.717
which draws the community
even closer together.

00:30:01.140 --> 00:30:03.692
Especially like on Friday nights
during football season,

00:30:03.693 --> 00:30:05.370
it is the biggest event.

00:30:05.370 --> 00:30:09.770
And the rivalries between
those three schools are second to none.

00:30:09.770 --> 00:30:14.333
If it's an away game, each town will
pretty much move their entire population

00:30:14.333 --> 00:30:17.417
over to the other town
to cheer on their team and

00:30:17.778 --> 00:30:19.390
have some really good football.

00:30:19.390 --> 00:30:21.025
-So it's a big deal here?
-It is.

00:30:21.025 --> 00:30:22.075
High school football.

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:24.193
What are those buses up there?

00:30:24.193 --> 00:30:26.965
-Inmates are getting bussed around?
-Yeah, probably. We'll follow it.

00:30:26.965 --> 00:30:30.293
I'm pretty sure it's gonna be
going to the Regional Medical Center,

00:30:30.293 --> 00:30:33.343
the biggest facility that they have
right here in Lake Butler.

00:30:33.700 --> 00:30:36.122
-That's connected with the prison system?

00:30:36.122 --> 00:30:36.916
-Yes.

00:30:36.916 --> 00:30:40.610
This is the one when people get sent
to the Department of Corrections,

00:30:40.610 --> 00:30:45.207
this part of the state, they all
come out here for their medical evaluation.

00:30:45.207 --> 00:30:47.909
If they have serious medical issues

00:30:48.432 --> 00:30:51.117
and need extended medical stays,

00:30:51.444 --> 00:30:53.353
they house them out here.

00:30:53.944 --> 00:30:57.253
[Peter] You've got to think that bus ride,
if you're an inmate, right?

00:30:57.637 --> 00:31:00.037
This bus ride has to be
the best thing happening.

00:31:00.341 --> 00:31:02.883
Just being sort of out
in society a little bit.

00:31:02.883 --> 00:31:04.190
-Yep.
-Beautiful road.

00:31:05.660 --> 00:31:07.948
No windows, so they can't break anything.

00:31:08.225 --> 00:31:11.233
Well, smaller windows
that they can't climb out of, yes.

00:31:11.460 --> 00:31:13.409
But this is the sports complex here.

00:31:13.937 --> 00:31:16.704
Baseball, football,
I think they even have soccer out here.

00:31:17.080 --> 00:31:19.920
-So it's just an intertwined
part of existence here.

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:20.730
-Yes.

00:31:20.730 --> 00:31:24.088
-The prisoners go by while you're playing
baseball and everything's normal.

00:31:24.088 --> 00:31:27.451
Well, you know, most of the coaches,
the parents of the kids that are out here,

00:31:27.451 --> 00:31:29.445
are employed at the prisons.

00:31:29.790 --> 00:31:33.468
So the doctors and nurses
that work in these facilities,

00:31:33.468 --> 00:31:34.766
do they train for this?

00:31:35.035 --> 00:31:36.564
I would think they have to be like…

00:31:36.565 --> 00:31:38.537
-They would be given, and continually,

00:31:38.537 --> 00:31:40.623
because there are certain
rules and procedures

00:31:40.624 --> 00:31:42.803
that they have to follow per state law.

00:31:43.156 --> 00:31:44.801
-This thing goes on forever.

00:31:44.801 --> 00:31:46.070
-It's giant.

00:31:46.070 --> 00:31:47.741
We're pretty much surrounded by it.

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:49.935
The camera doesn't do it all,
unfortunately.

00:31:49.935 --> 00:31:53.355
I don't have a zoom lens with this,
but it's pretty much all around us.

00:31:53.355 --> 00:31:55.671
There's actually nice grounds here,
I gotta say.

00:31:55.671 --> 00:31:56.758
It's beautiful out here.

00:31:56.758 --> 00:31:59.710
It's manicured
and taken care of by the inmates.

00:31:59.710 --> 00:32:01.130
Oh, the inmates are doing all this.

00:32:01.130 --> 00:32:03.047
-They're cleaning all this up.
-Mowing it.

00:32:03.689 --> 00:32:05.139
[Brad] Those are two inmates.

00:32:06.207 --> 00:32:09.506
[cell phone rings]

00:32:09.506 --> 00:32:11.710
-Hey, Brett.
-Man, where are y'all located?

00:32:12.060 --> 00:32:15.970
We are crossing the runway out here at RMC.

00:32:15.970 --> 00:32:17.520
-Yeah, I'll meet you back there.

00:32:19.826 --> 00:32:21.820
[Peter] So, Brad sort of
suckered you into this.

00:32:21.820 --> 00:32:23.301
[Brett] Yeah, that's right.

00:32:23.301 --> 00:32:25.273
All right.
So, Brad, we're going to let you chill.

00:32:25.273 --> 00:32:26.905
-Good.
-You get a break from me.

00:32:26.912 --> 00:32:28.037
It's probably a good thing.

00:32:28.037 --> 00:32:31.370
-We can walk. Are you cool with walking?
-Yeah, man. It's so beautiful. Absolutely.

00:32:31.370 --> 00:32:34.155
And Brett, you worked
in corrections for how long?

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:39.195
I was with the department
for right at about 17 years.

00:32:39.454 --> 00:32:40.818
When did you start? How old?

00:32:40.818 --> 00:32:44.285
I started here
at the reception and medical center.

00:32:44.285 --> 00:32:47.893
I was 19 years old,
freshly out of high school.

00:32:48.430 --> 00:32:49.988
I had a young family.

00:32:50.515 --> 00:32:54.876
And, quite frankly,
just needed a job with benefits.

00:32:54.876 --> 00:32:58.026
And, you know, it was
a great opportunity to start a retirement.

00:32:58.390 --> 00:33:01.851
And it's one of those things
that I never really thought

00:33:01.851 --> 00:33:04.310
I was going to have to think of
so early in life.

00:33:04.310 --> 00:33:08.478
But starting a family,
you know, that age, you know,

00:33:08.478 --> 00:33:11.284
it was just something that was necessary.

00:33:11.910 --> 00:33:16.658
It's certainly not your
regular 8 to 5 desk job.

00:33:17.240 --> 00:33:19.350
But I'll tell you, I have no regrets.

00:33:19.620 --> 00:33:21.763
It was probably one of
the best decisions I ever made.

00:33:21.763 --> 00:33:22.843
Really? Okay.

00:33:22.843 --> 00:33:27.749
And that is a city in and of itself.

00:33:27.749 --> 00:33:28.475
Okay.

00:33:28.475 --> 00:33:32.343
It essentially has everything that we have.

00:33:32.636 --> 00:33:35.042
Its own governing laws,

00:33:35.043 --> 00:33:37.680
its own rules and regulations.

00:33:37.680 --> 00:33:40.846
You know, out here we have speed limits
and those sorts of things.

00:33:40.846 --> 00:33:44.153
And they have
just their different set of rules

00:33:44.154 --> 00:33:46.193
and regulations that they live by.

00:33:46.260 --> 00:33:49.822
It is something that people
don't know about.

00:33:50.216 --> 00:33:54.366
They don't know much about
what the daily routine is

00:33:54.366 --> 00:33:57.016
for any of these guys
that work here in these prisons.

00:33:57.800 --> 00:33:59.628
In all reality, just the sheer

00:34:00.554 --> 00:34:04.120
level of skill that it takes
just to communicate.

00:34:04.120 --> 00:34:07.926
There's such a diverse population
inside of those fences.

00:34:08.490 --> 00:34:11.825
Many of the folks that work in
these facilities

00:34:11.825 --> 00:34:13.309
are from the local areas.

00:34:14.560 --> 00:34:18.690
In our area, right here
in the heart of North Central Florida,

00:34:18.690 --> 00:34:22.080
there's diversity in the population
outside of the prison.

00:34:22.080 --> 00:34:24.333
But whenever you get inside there,

00:34:24.733 --> 00:34:27.400
it is all worlds that come together.

00:34:27.400 --> 00:34:28.160
-Oh yeah.

00:34:28.160 --> 00:34:31.167
And just having the skills to communicate,

00:34:31.167 --> 00:34:34.290
maintain order,
and just make things happen.

00:34:34.523 --> 00:34:37.745
-And I can imagine
a lot of the people in here,

00:34:38.050 --> 00:34:41.754
their emotional intelligence
is like an 11 out of 10.

00:34:41.754 --> 00:34:42.540
Oh yeah.

00:34:42.540 --> 00:34:45.755
They know how to manipulate.
They're street smarts.

00:34:45.755 --> 00:34:46.740
Sure.

00:34:46.740 --> 00:34:48.347
So if you're going there weak…

00:34:48.998 --> 00:34:49.687
Yeah.

00:34:49.687 --> 00:34:51.701
…as a corrections officer,
you're not on, right?

00:34:51.701 --> 00:34:53.960
-No.
-It's a code of respect?

00:34:54.620 --> 00:34:55.620
It is.

00:34:55.840 --> 00:35:00.842
I know a lot of folks
have an us versus them type mentality.

00:35:01.230 --> 00:35:02.880
And in a sense, it is.

00:35:03.352 --> 00:35:05.455
-Sure.
-If you think about it like this…

00:35:05.455 --> 00:35:08.194
…these officers that work here,

00:35:08.547 --> 00:35:12.888
they're here for their 8 hours
or 12 hours, whatever their shift is.

00:35:13.290 --> 00:35:17.630
But there's always kind of a light
at the end of the tunnel for them.

00:35:17.630 --> 00:35:20.654
They know that whenever
they're scheduled to go home,

00:35:21.025 --> 00:35:22.459
they get to leave this behind.

00:35:22.459 --> 00:35:24.876
And they get to go to
their husbands and their wives

00:35:24.876 --> 00:35:26.820
and their kids and those sorts of things.

00:35:26.820 --> 00:35:29.161
And they kind of set this aside.

00:35:29.161 --> 00:35:29.924
-Mm-hmm.

00:35:29.924 --> 00:35:31.181
The guys that live here,

00:35:32.396 --> 00:35:34.252
they have 24-7

00:35:34.719 --> 00:35:36.731
to think about how to manipulate,

00:35:37.214 --> 00:35:39.293
how to make things happen their way.

00:35:39.551 --> 00:35:42.330
And so you've really got to be diligent.

00:35:42.807 --> 00:35:46.605
On your toes, so to speak,
whenever you're here and supervising.

00:35:46.930 --> 00:35:49.969
Oftentimes, there's one person supervising

00:35:49.970 --> 00:35:53.501
well over a hundred inmates at one time.

00:35:54.020 --> 00:35:56.405
So if you don't know
how to handle yourself

00:35:56.991 --> 00:35:59.120
and to communicate,
it can be very difficult.

00:35:59.120 --> 00:36:00.169
-You're on your toes?

00:36:00.169 --> 00:36:01.169
Absolutely.

00:36:01.500 --> 00:36:03.070
-Dangerous?
-Dangerous.

00:36:03.070 --> 00:36:05.590
I mean, okay, you leave
your wife and kids in the morning.

00:36:05.590 --> 00:36:07.709
Slight chance a shank comes at you.

00:36:07.709 --> 00:36:09.902
Something happens every day.

00:36:10.479 --> 00:36:11.479
High stress.

00:36:12.224 --> 00:36:13.224
Then you clock out.

00:36:13.908 --> 00:36:16.294
You go home.
You might be the little league coach.

00:36:16.531 --> 00:36:17.531
Oh, yeah.

00:36:17.531 --> 00:36:19.931
You might just
go get an ice cream with the kids.

00:36:20.590 --> 00:36:23.320
And you just, what do you do,
just flip the switch every day?

00:36:23.320 --> 00:36:24.384
Well, you have to.

00:36:24.680 --> 00:36:27.380
It's just a means of dealing with stress.

00:36:27.380 --> 00:36:28.430
Everyone's different.

00:36:28.790 --> 00:36:29.574
Yeah.

00:36:29.574 --> 00:36:33.352
Personally, whenever I was working here,
I did have young families.

00:36:33.725 --> 00:36:35.659
I did coach the little league teams.

00:36:35.659 --> 00:36:36.659
Okay, that was you.

00:36:36.659 --> 00:36:39.349
The Pop Warner football teams
or something year-round.

00:36:39.870 --> 00:36:43.818
And just being involved
in your regular activities.

00:36:44.090 --> 00:36:45.663
But still, whenever,

00:36:46.331 --> 00:36:49.720
you know, it may be midnight
that you're coming in.

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:51.777
That's the way it was whenever I started.

00:36:52.153 --> 00:36:54.162
I left home at 11:30.

00:36:54.162 --> 00:36:54.849
Okay.

00:36:54.849 --> 00:36:56.963
Whenever all of my family
was going to sleep.

00:36:57.540 --> 00:36:59.440
And you stayed up all night.

00:36:59.736 --> 00:37:02.325
And whenever you leave,
everybody's getting ready to go to school

00:37:02.325 --> 00:37:03.860
and go about their regular day.

00:37:04.290 --> 00:37:05.290
And you sleep.

00:37:06.128 --> 00:37:07.128
[laughs]

00:37:07.129 --> 00:37:10.814
Did you feel like nobody
could understand you who's not in there?

00:37:10.814 --> 00:37:12.942
Oh, that's for sure.

00:37:13.430 --> 00:37:15.870
It's been a good amount of years

00:37:15.871 --> 00:37:18.209
since I worked here.

00:37:18.540 --> 00:37:23.140
I can see people
that I haven't seen in many years.

00:37:23.140 --> 00:37:25.361
Guys and men and women

00:37:25.968 --> 00:37:26.968
that

00:37:27.973 --> 00:37:30.424
we worked together for some time.

00:37:30.424 --> 00:37:32.112
It may have been 20 years ago.

00:37:32.112 --> 00:37:33.662
But whenever we see each other,

00:37:34.330 --> 00:37:36.340
it's almost like a special bond.

00:37:36.961 --> 00:37:41.140
You know, it's almost like you have
never been away from each other.

00:37:41.140 --> 00:37:43.665
Your relationships pick up
right where they left off.

00:37:43.665 --> 00:37:44.665
-Oh, yeah.

00:37:44.665 --> 00:37:48.258
It's just kind of a fraternity,
so to speak.

00:37:48.919 --> 00:37:50.300
Before I was 30,

00:37:51.240 --> 00:37:54.051
I saw so many things

00:37:54.543 --> 00:37:56.778
that I probably wouldn't have normally seen

00:37:56.778 --> 00:38:00.902
just living out on,
you know, in the free world.

00:38:01.380 --> 00:38:04.667
It wasn't here,
but there was an institution that I was at

00:38:04.667 --> 00:38:07.180
that, you know,
you saw a little more violence.

00:38:07.180 --> 00:38:10.372
I was a first responder

00:38:10.831 --> 00:38:11.983
to a case where

00:38:12.490 --> 00:38:14.531
another inmate had attacked one

00:38:14.531 --> 00:38:18.513
and I guess the term would be the shank,

00:38:18.513 --> 00:38:21.129
but an ice pick style weapon

00:38:21.605 --> 00:38:24.607
had stabbed this other guy.

00:38:24.607 --> 00:38:27.877
I think the final count
was over a hundred times

00:38:28.379 --> 00:38:30.580
between the neck and his waist.

00:38:30.580 --> 00:38:35.062
And that was
a pretty rough set right there.

00:38:35.450 --> 00:38:37.159
You have to go hands on.

00:38:38.255 --> 00:38:42.514
Because not only are you
responsible for the security.

00:38:42.950 --> 00:38:45.702
Making sure these guys are still there.

00:38:46.350 --> 00:38:48.613
You're also responsible
for their well-being.

00:38:49.069 --> 00:38:51.395
These correctional officers,
if they see an inmate

00:38:51.396 --> 00:38:53.909
that is in a life or death situation,

00:38:54.503 --> 00:38:58.220
they're going to do everything that
they can possibly do to save that life.

00:38:58.543 --> 00:39:01.053
Because that inmate is in the care

00:39:01.643 --> 00:39:03.381
of the department as well.

00:39:03.797 --> 00:39:06.098
And so, you know, a lot of times

00:39:06.759 --> 00:39:09.884
things are looked at
negatively from more of a

00:39:10.691 --> 00:39:13.221
discipline point of view. Okay?

00:39:13.221 --> 00:39:18.217
These "guards", as a lot of people
refer to these officers as,

00:39:18.660 --> 00:39:20.923
their job is just to be mean and to punish.

00:39:21.685 --> 00:39:24.891
That's not necessarily the case at all.

00:39:25.460 --> 00:39:29.535
What people don't hear
is whenever these officers

00:39:29.867 --> 00:39:33.678
make life-saving decisions
to help these guys.

00:39:34.120 --> 00:39:35.569
To administer CPR.

00:39:35.930 --> 00:39:40.994
To put their hands over wounds
that are bleeding profusely.

00:39:41.410 --> 00:39:43.049
It's just a full circle of life.

00:39:43.273 --> 00:39:46.030
You know, you work there.

00:39:46.030 --> 00:39:48.914
You live a portion of your life there.

00:39:49.190 --> 00:39:53.404
But never forget that
anyone that is under your custody

00:39:53.404 --> 00:39:54.953
is also under your care.

00:39:54.953 --> 00:39:56.849
And you're responsible for that life.

00:39:57.395 --> 00:40:00.039
And so, just kind of
a different outlook

00:40:00.039 --> 00:40:02.289
that a lot of people
won't really think about.

00:40:03.170 --> 00:40:05.709
[Brett] You're getting a suntan.
He's rolling his sleeves up.

00:40:05.709 --> 00:40:07.695
[Peter] Well guys,
interesting stuff out here.

00:40:07.952 --> 00:40:09.643
At least for me as an outsider.

00:40:09.943 --> 00:40:12.284
-You know, it's just normal life here.
-Yeah.

00:40:12.284 --> 00:40:14.021
You know, we don't think about it

00:40:14.021 --> 00:40:16.870
until somebody that
isn't around it on a regular basis,

00:40:16.870 --> 00:40:19.143
kind of like you or some of your viewers,

00:40:19.460 --> 00:40:22.181
We don't think of it as anything
out of the ordinary.

00:40:22.480 --> 00:40:24.415
And we love having it here.

00:40:24.415 --> 00:40:27.328
The people that work in there
are just incredible people.

00:40:27.747 --> 00:40:29.380
People are very nice in your towns here.

00:40:29.880 --> 00:40:30.910
Yeah.

00:40:30.910 --> 00:40:33.594
-I just got in last night.
-It's the heartbeat of Florida.

00:40:33.594 --> 00:40:34.862
It is, huh?

00:40:34.862 --> 00:40:36.004
Those are fighting words.

00:40:36.005 --> 00:40:38.662
You can't get to heaven
without going through Bradford.

00:40:38.662 --> 00:40:40.058
-Oh.
-[Brett] Or Union.

00:40:40.323 --> 00:40:41.870
-Or Union, or Baker.

00:40:41.870 --> 00:40:45.267
Thanks for showing me a little today
and sharing your story.

00:40:45.538 --> 00:40:47.964
Thanks for being on camera
'cause that's really hard to find.

00:40:47.964 --> 00:40:49.766
-Absolutely. Yeah, man.
-Appreciate that.

00:40:50.045 --> 00:40:51.877
Brad, appreciate it.

00:40:51.877 --> 00:40:54.308
All right, guys.
Thanks for coming on that journey.

00:40:54.309 --> 00:40:55.309
Until the next one.

00:40:56.302 --> 00:40:57.302
[country music]

